Wallace Ad intended
To the Editor:
In her letter about why the
5&3 should not have printed
the Wallace ad, Kit order
seems to have missed the point
completely. Freedom of speech
is very much the issue on this
question —— the content of the
ad is not our concern.
The ad was prepared by Wa1<
lace people as part of a nationwide advertising campaign
directed at college computer.
Its purpose, like almost all political advertising, was to get
as many votes as possible for
the Candidate, It was Wallace's
decision that this style of ad,
which like most political advertising decided most of the issues, would get the most votes
for Wallace from the college
community. If a college newspaper choices to carry any po«
optical advertising, it then has
the obligation to accept all p0<
optical advertisiing. To do otherwise would be to engage in selective membership of political
views.
it every newspaper followed
its editorial policy in accepting
advertising (many papers in
the South do this in fact) we
would not have seen McCarthy
ads in most papers and we
would not see ads to stop the
booking of North Vietnam,
sponsored by long lists of college processors, which regulatory appear in the New York
Times.
One could of course say that
Wallace is a racing, fastest, unexpected, structured slow and
that he dress't merit serious attention. But that would mean
s line will have to be drawn
between “good" and “bad"
and, as in every membership
question, this is impossible to
do in the context of freedom
of thought
If there is anywhere in society
that freedom or thought and
action must be deferred, it is
on the college campus.
Henry Wilhelm
